The structure of CMCel was firstly analyzed using XRD. Detailed experimental synthesis and characterizations were provided in Supporting Information. As shown in Fig. 1 a, the diffraction patterns match well with those of hexagonal Mg(OH)2 (JCPDS# 44–1482). It indicates the presence of the brucite Mg(OH)2 [55] in the composite. Characteristic peaks at 14.6°, 16.3° and 22.6° can be assigned to the (101), (10
1 ¯
) and (002) plane of cellulose I (JCPDS# 50–2241). There are the FT-IR spectra of CMCel recorded in Fig. 1b also show the existence of Mg(OH)2. The peak at 3690 cm–1 corresponds to the (Mg)OH stretching vibrational mode, confirming the presence of Mg(OH)2. Other characteristic peaks observed at 3332, 2902 and 1056 cm–1 is attributed to the OH stretching vibration, asymmetrically stretched CH in the pyran ring and CO stretch, respectively. Their slight shift compared with precursors implies the interaction between cellulose and Mg(OH)2 in the composite. By inspecting detailed interfacial atoms, the interaction mainly arises from hydroxyls of cellulose and Mg(OH)2, which remain consistent regardless of the morphology and size of cellulose.

In describing the process that CMCel adsorbs Pb ion, the structure of carbon dots-Mg(OH)2-cellulose·Pb(NO3)2(H2O) (marked as CMCel·PbNO3
                        ) was optimized. Four energetically stable isomers were obtained as shown in Fig. S7. They are all exothermic reactions (Table 2
                        ), in which CMCel·PbNO3_1 releases the most energy, −1.516 eV in total energy (ΔrE) and −0.650 eV in free energy (ΔrG). To simulate the resulting cellulose-precipitate, cellulose·Pb(CO3)(H2O)2 (Cel·PbCO3
                        ) and cellulose·Pb(OH)2(H2O)2 (Cel·PbOH) have been considered. Seven and three isomers were obtained, respectively, in Figs. S8 and S9. The reaction energies of forming Cel·PbCO3_1 and Cel·PbOH_1 are −1.275 eV and −1.062 eV in ΔrE, respectively, along with −0.511 and −0.407 eV in ΔrG. That is, the formation of cellulose-precipitate complex is thermodynamically feasible reaction, which provides sound theoretical backing for the experimental characterization results. Moreover, they are stabilized by electrostatic and orbital attractions (Table S6).
